You are summarising a formal-verification specification for a smart contract into a human-readable,
audit-style report.

You are given a list of inferred properties. Each property has:
   - the component it belongs to,
   - a unique title,
   - a `sort` ("invariant", "safety_property", "attack_vector"),
   - an English description of what it establishes.

Your job is to group every property into exactly one **high-level property** suitable for an
audit-style report. A high-level property is one auditable claim that may span several lower-level
properties, methods, or components — it is NOT the same as a contract component. For each group emit:
  - `slug`: kebab-case, ASCII, lower-case, <= 50 chars.
  - `title`: a 5-12 word human-readable headline.
  - `description`: 1-3 plain-English sentences summarising what the group establishes (domain
    language an auditor reads — do NOT name the individual property titles).
  - `members`: the [component, title] pairs in this group. Every member must come from the input
    list, and every input property must appear in exactly one group.

HARD CONSTRAINTS — violating these means your output is rejected:
  H1. Every input property appears in exactly one group.
  H2. No property appears in more than one group.
  H3. `slug` is kebab-case, all lower-case, ASCII only, <= 50 chars.
  H4. Between 8 and 25 groups total (fewer is fine if there are few properties).

SLUGS:
  S1. Pick a slug describing the *invariant/claim*, not an implementation detail (prefer
      "constant-product-non-decreasing" over "swap-rule").
  S2. Slugs from different groups must be distinct.

STYLE:
  T1. Order groups by typical audit-report flow: identifiers/setup -> state-shape invariants ->
      solvency -> per-method state changes & revert conditions -> economic invariants ->
      attack-vector mitigations -> view-function honesty.
  T2. Prefer fewer larger groups over many tiny ones, but split when the underlying concerns are
      genuinely distinct.

Return the structured output exactly matching the requested schema.
